      10             : /*
      11             : 
      12             : attribute.c -- Processing of attributes.
      13             : 
      14             : 
      15             : How to Add a New Attribute
      16             : ==========================
      17             : The attribute framework is designed to make it relatively easy to add a new
      18             : attribute.  Typically, adding an attribute involves just a few steps:
      19             : 
      20             :   (1) Add a new ak_... attribute kind constant in il_def.h.
      21             :       For example: ak_section.
      22             : 
      23             :   (2) Add a new row to the table known_attr_table[] below.  For example:
      24             :         { "section", "(sn)", "gx", ak_section },
      25             :       Such a row describes the source form of the attribute ("section"),
      26             :       what kind of arguments (if any) the attribute takes ("(sn)" means that
      27             :       a normal string literal is expected), and which mode the attribute
      28             :       should be accepted in ("gx" means that all GNU C and C++ modes should
      29             :       accept the attribute).
      30             :       See the definition of struct an_attr_descr for details.
      31             : 
      32             :   (3) Add a new row to the table known_attr_appl_table[] below.  For example:
      33             :         { ak_section, "r|v:-a!", apply_section_attr },
      34             :       Such a row describes simple constraints for the entity to which the
      35             :       attribute is applied ("r|v:-a!" means that the entity must be a routine
      36             :       or a non-automatic variable), and which function to call to "apply" the
      37             :       attribute (apply_section_attr in this case) which may check additional
      38             :       constraints and/or update the IL entry for the entity.  (If no function
      39             :       should be called, specify NO_APPL_FN instead.)
      40             :       See the definition of struct an_attr_appl_descr for details.
      41             : 
      42             :   (4) Write the application function specified in step 3 (if any).
      43             : 
      44             :   (5) If needed, update the table attr_corresp_table[] below to customize
      45             :       the rules for handling corresponding attributes across translation
      46             :       units (by default corresponding attributes must match exactly; see
      47             :       the definition of an_attr_corresp_descr for details).
      48             : 
      49             : Even when none of these steps is taken, an unrecognized attribute will still
      50             : automatically be recorded in the IL when record_unrecognized_attributes is
      51             : TRUE (when FALSE, a warning is issued for unrecognized attributes). 
      52             : 
      53             : For attributes that are only of interest to a back end, it is conceivable that
      54             : no application function is required or that the application function does not
      55             : update the target IL entry because the an_attribute entry that is automatically
      56             : recorded is sufficient for the back end (ak_carries_dependency is currently an
      57             : example of the latter).
      58             : 
      59             : It is recommended that attributes not produce an entirely new IL entry, but
      60             : instead just modify the entry they apply to "in place".  Some GNU attributes
      61             : (mode and vector_size) do however produce a new a_type entry when applied to
      62             : another a_type entry.  For that reason, the application function type is:
      63             :     typedef char* an_attr_application_fn(an_attribute_ptr  ap,
      64             :                                          char              *entity,
      65             :                                          an_il_entry_kind  entity_kind);
      66             : The returned value is the entity resulting from applying the given attribute
      67             : to the given entity (in most cases the returned entity is the given entity,
      68             : since attributes usually do not create new entries).
      69             : */
      70             :

      72             : #include "fe_common.h"

     104             : 
     105             : #define MAX_ATTRIBUTE_NAME_LENGTH 100
     106             : 
     107             : typedef struct an_attr_descr *an_attr_descr_ptr;
     108             : typedef struct an_attr_descr {
     109             :   /* Data structure describing the name and kind of an attribute, the form
     110             :      of its arguments if any (i.e., its "signature"), and the modes in which
     111             :      that attribute should be recognized.  This defines the structure of the
     112             :      table known_attr_table (below) of recognizable attributes. */
     113             :   a_const_char  *name;
     114             :                         /* The name of the attribute.  If an attribute name
     115             :                            can include optional leading/trailing underscores,
     116             :                            those underscores are not included here.  The name
     117             :                            may not be longer than MAX_ATTRIBUTE_NAME_LENGTH. */
     118             :   a_const_char  *sig;
     119             :                         /* A compact encoding of the "signature" of this
     120             :                            attribute.  If sig is "", no attribute arguments
     121             :                            are permitted.  If sig starts with "?", arguments
     122             :                            are optional.  The arguments are described by a
     123             :                            parenthesized comma-separated list of codes (no
     124             :                            spaces are permitted):
     125             :                              "t": a type-id is expected
     126             :                              "ci": an integer constant is expected
     127             :                              "ct": an integer constant or a type is expected
     128             :                                    (similar to a "sizeof(...)" argument)
     129             :                              "n": an identifier is expected
     130             :                              "sn": a narrow string literal is expected
     131             :                              "sx": a string literal is expected (wide/narrow)
     132             :                              "X": an expression
     133             :                              "*": an arbitrary set of tokens is expected
     134             :                                   (this can only be for the last argument)
     135             :                            A code can be followed by a "+" to indicate that
     136             :                            one or more arguments of that kind are expected.
     137             :                            A "?" indicates that the argument list may
     138             :                            terminate at that point.
     139             :                            Examples:
     140             :                              "(ci)": one integer constant required
     141             :                              "(?sn+)": one or more string literals are
     142             :                                  optional, but the enclosing parentheses are
     143             :                                  required (i.e., attr() or attr("str", "ing")
     144             :                                  are okay, but just attr is not).
     145             :                              "(n?,t,ci)": an identifier is required; it can
     146             :                                  optionally be followed by a type and an
     147             :                                  integer constant (both or neither).
     148             :                              "?(n?,t?,ci)": either no argument list appears at
     149             :                                  all, or an identifier appears, optionally
     150             :                                  followed by a type, itself optionally followed
     151             :                                  by an integer constant.
     152             :                         */
     153             :   a_const_char  *cond;
     154             :                         /* A compact encoding of the condition in which this
     155             :                            attribute is accepted.  The encoding consists of an
     156             :                            optional prefix (see below) followed by a condition
     157             :                            string cstr.  cstr[0] indicates the attribute
     158             :                            family: 'c' for [[...]] (standard C++11), 'g' for
     159             :                            __attribute((...)) in GNU modes, 's' for
     160             :                            __attribute((...)) in Sun mode, 'l' for
     161             :                            __attribute((...)) in Clang mode, and 'm' for
     162             :                            __declspec(...) in Microsoft mode.  cstr[1] is
     163             :                            '+' if the attribute only applies in C++ modes,
     164             :                            'c' if it only applies in C mode, and 'x' if it
     165             :                            applies in both C and C++ modes (some combinations
     166             :                            are impossible; e.g. "sc" is meaningless since there
     167             :                            is no "Sun C" mode).  For standard attributes, the
     168             :                            first two characters can be followed by a bracketed
     169             :                            namespace name.  E.g., if name is "test" and cstr
     170             :                            is "c+[xyz]", then this is a description entry for
     171             :                            [[xyz::test ... ]].  If cstr[0] is 'g', 'l' or 'm',
     172             :                            the first two characters can be followed by a
     173             :                            parenthesized range of applicable versions.  E.g.,
     174             :                            "gx(30100-39999)" means the attribute is valid in 
     175             :                            GNU C/C++ modes with gnu_version >= 30100 and
     176             :                            gnu_version < 40000.  Either end of the range can
     177             :                            be dropped; e.g., "mc(1400-)" means the attribute
     178             :                            is valid in Microsoft C mode with microsoft_version
     179             :                            >= 1400.  For standard-notation attributes, a range
     180             :                            of values for std_version can also be provided (it
     181             :                            should appear after the bracketed namespace name, if
     182             :                            any).
     183             : 
     184             :                            Auxiliary version specification(s) can also be
     185             :                            specified by appending "|", one of "C", "G", "M", or
     186             :                            "S" (for clang_version, gnu_version,
     187             :                            microsoft_version, and std_version respectively) and
     188             :                            an applicable version range.  The auxiliary version
     189             :                            specifier doesn't affect the attribute family.  For
     190             :                            example, "1c+(201701-|M(1910-))" specifies a
     191             :                            standard attribute that is available when
     192             :                            std_version >= 201701 or when microsoft_version >=
     193             :                            1910.
     194             : 
     195             :                            A prefix "1" means the attribute can appear at most
     196             :                            once per attribute group.  E.g., "1c+" indicates a
     197             :                            standard C++ attribute that can appear at most once
     198             :                            in a attribute group (and with no namespace). */
     199             :   an_attribute_kind
     200             :                 attr_kind;
     201             :                         /* The attribute kind to record in the corresponding
     202             :                            attribute entry. */
     203             : } an_attr_descr;
     204             :

     408             :   a_const_char  *target_constraints;
     409             :                         /* A compact description of the kind of target entity
     410             :                            that this attribute can be applied to.  If this is
     411             :                            the empty string, the attributes apply to any entity
     412             :                            a priori (though appl_fn can impose limitations of
     413             :                            its own).  Otherwise, the string consists of one or
     414             :                            more entity kind descriptions separated by "|".
     415             :                            Each entity kind description is a single character
     416             :                            describing the broad kind of entity (e.g., "r" for
     417             :                            "routine"), optionally prefixed by "W" or followed
     418             :                            by ":" and one or more "property switches".  The
     419             :                            "W" prefix indicates that the entity kind is not a
     420             :                            match, but that only a warning should be issued if
     421             :                            an attribute is applied to such an entity. The
     422             :                            property switches are of the form "+x" or "-x"
     423             :                            where "x" is a character representing a property.
     424             :                            The "+x" form indicates that the property is
     425             :                            required whereas the "-x" for indicates that it is
     426             :                            prohibited.  For example, "r" means the attribute
     427             :                            is allowed on any routine, "r:+v" means it applies
     428             :                            only on virtual routines, and "r:-v" means it
     429             :                            applies only on nonvirtual routines.  Here is the
     430             :                            set of entity codes and property codes currently
     431             :                            recognized:
     432             :                              "T"  : type-transforming (must be first)
     433             :                              "t"  : types
     434             :                                "f"  : function types
     435             :                              "c"  : class type (after "class", "struct", or
     436             :                                       "union" keyword)
     437             :                                "d"  : class definition
     438             :                              "e"  : enum type (after "enum" or "enum class")
     439             :                                "d"  : enum definition
     440             :                              "E"  : enumerator constant
     441             :                                (no property switches)
     442             :                              "r"  : routines
     443             :                                "m"  : class member
     444             :                                "i"  : inline
     445             :                                "p"  : pure virtual
     446             :                                "v"  : virtual
     447             :                                "x"  : external linkage
     448             :                              "v"  : variables
     449             :                                "a"  : automatic variables
     450             :                                "h"  : exception handler parameter variable
     451             :                                "l"  : local variables (automatic/static)
     452             :                                "r"  : register variables
     453             :                                "x"  : external linkage
     454             :                              "p"  : parameters
     455             :                                (no property switches)
     456             :                              "d"  : fields
     457             :                                "b"  : bit field
     458             :                              "u"  : using-declarations/using-directives
     459             :                                (no property switches)
     460             :                              "n"  : namespaces
     461             :                                (no property switches)
     462             :                              "s"  : statements
     463             :                                (no property switches)
     464             :                              "l"  : labels
     465             :                                (no property switches)
     466             :                              "0"  : stand-alone attribute (no target entity)
     467             :                                (no property switches)
     468             :                            A switch is optionally followed by a "!" to indicate
     469             :                            that a failure to meet the requirement should be
     470             :                            diagnosed as a hard error (otherwise, it elicits a
     471             :                            warning).  For example "v:-r|d:-b!" means that the
     472             :                            attribute applies to non-register variables and to
     473             :                            fields that aren't bit fields: When applied to a
     474             :                            register variable, a warning is issued, but when
     475             :                            applied to a bit field an error is issued.  Note
     476             :                            the "T" code which is special: If it is present, it
     477             :                            must be first and it indicates that it applies to a
     478             :                            type by producing a new type entry (instead of
     479             :                            modifying an existing type entry "in place").
     480             :                            If an attribute fails to meet the constraints
     481             :                            encoded here, that attribute is reclassified as
     482             :                            ak_unrecognized.  This is true even if the failure 
     483             :                            only triggers a warning (because of a 'W' prefix on
     484             :                            the entity code, or the lack of a '!' suffix on a
     485             :                            property switch). */
     486             :   an_attr_application_fn
     487             :                 *appl_fn;
     488             :                         /* NULL or a pointer to the function to call to apply
     489             :                            the attribute to the entity it appertains to.  (Such
     490             :                            a function could enforce constraints and/or reflect
     491             :                            the attribute in some aspects of the IL.) */
     492             : } an_attr_appl_descr;

     762             : typedef struct an_attr_corresp_descr *an_attr_corresp_descr_ptr;
     763             : typedef struct an_attr_corresp_descr {
     764             :   /* Data structure describing special rules when checking attributes on
     765             :      corresponding entities across translation units.  (If an attribute
     766             :      kind/family/target-entity triple does not appear in this table, it is
     767             :      assumed that that kind of attribute must match exactly across

     777             :                            is meant (e.g., an attribute X may apply to both
     778             :                            variables and types, but the handling of cross-
     779             :                            translation-unit correspondences may be different
